<hr />
<p><font color="darkred">ED FRIERSON</font> submitted <strong>FLUTTER! Wisdom For Living, Loving, Dying</strong> designed by Christopher Darling. &#8220;The cover features original, hand-drawn, butterfly wings having species integrity. It replicates the cover of main character Casey&#8217;s wisdom revealing &#8220;Bug Book.&#8221; The compelling cover wonder fills a dramatic scene when the notebook unexpectedly appears for the first time&#8230;at Casey&#8217;s memorial.&#8221;<br />
<br /><img src="http://www.thebookdesigner.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/01/Flutter.jpg" alt="FLUTTER! Wisdom For Living, Loving, Dying" title="FLUTTER! Wisdom For Living, Loving, Dying" width="200" /></a><br />
<strong><font color="crimson">JF:</font> </strong>I&#8217;m sure people who buy and read this book will be very happy to see the story reflected in the cover. However, in general we design covers for those people who <em>haven&#8217;t</em> read it yet, and the problem I have with this cover, pretty though it is, is that it&#8217;s hard to make out what I&#8217;m looking at at a small size and I&#8217;m not sure why I&#8217;m supposed to be interested. By the way, your subtitle seems to belong on a self-help book, not a novel.</p>
